skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowColor #333333
skinparam packageStyle rectangle
skinparam defaultTextAlignment center
skinparam maxMessageSize 300

rectangle " APPLICATION LAYER " as LAYER1 #E1F5FE {
  rectangle "User Application" as USER_APP {
    card "main()" as USER_CODE
    card "VehicleMonitor<R>" as USER_MONITOR
  }
}

note bottom of LAYER1
  Application code using generic runtime APIs,
  which are platform-independent.
  main() function initializes the runtime and sets up producers/consumers.
end note

rectangle " ABSTRACTION LAYER " as LAYER2 #C8E6C9 {
  card "Concept Traits(com-api-concept)\nRuntime, Subscriber, Publisher" as TRAITS
  card " Interface specific type(generated-code-interface-specific)\nConsumer, Producer, Interface" as GEN_API
}

note bottom of LAYER2
  Abstraction layer defining generic traits and interfaces for COM API.
  It includes concept traits for communication backends and
  generated interface-specific types for consumers and producers.
  It is independent of any specific runtime implementation, and interface oriented.
end note

rectangle " RUNTIME LAYER " as LAYER3 #FFCCBC {
  card "LolaRuntimeImpl(com-api-runtime-lola)\nTrait Implementations" as RUNTIME_BUILD
}

note bottom of LAYER3
  This contains the concrete LoLa runtime implementation,
  This layer is responsible for all runtime operations of lola specific logic.
  It implements consumer side find/subscribe/receive,
  and producer side offer/allocate/publish operations.
  It maintains the runtime lifecycle and resource management.
end note

rectangle " FFI BRIDGE LAYER " as LAYER4 #FFE0B2 {
  card "Rust-C++ Bindings with help of \n Type Registry" as FFI_BRIDGE
}

note bottom of LAYER4
  Rust-C++ FFI bridge layer that facilitates communication between Rust runtime and C++ middleware.
  It contains the necessary bindings and type registry to enable seamless interoperability between the two languages.
  Rust code in the runtime layer can invoke C++ middleware functions through this bridge, and C++ code can call back into Rust as needed.
end note

rectangle " C++ IMPLEMENTATION LAYER for FFI " as LAYER5 #D1C4E9 {
  card "Generated C++ Code\nType Exports" as CPP_CODE
  card "C++ Macro and Type Registry\nFFI Support" as FFI_SUPPORT
  card "C++ mw::com API\nProxy/Skeleton, Events" as CPP_CLASSES
}

note bottom of LAYER5
  Exports the C++ COM API as a Rust FFI compatible API.
  Contains generated C++ code for type exports,
  FFI support macros and type registry for managing Rust-C++ interactions,
  And it calls the Core C++ middleware API for COM operations.
end note

USER_CODE --> RUNTIME_BUILD: instantiate
USER_MONITOR --> TRAITS: uses
USER_MONITOR --> GEN_API: parametrized by

RUNTIME_BUILD --> TRAITS: implements
GEN_API --> TRAITS: depends on

RUNTIME_BUILD --> FFI_BRIDGE: bridges via
FFI_BRIDGE --> FFI_SUPPORT: interacts with
CPP_CODE --> FFI_SUPPORT: registers
FFI_SUPPORT --> CPP_CLASSES: invokes

@enduml
